ncreased risk of breast and ovarian cancer. She refuses to inform her sister about this finding, despite the sister having a 50% chance of carrying the same variant. The sister could benefit from enhanced cancer screening if she also carries the variant.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ethical obligations of the healthcare provider in this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Require the patient to inform her sister","Respect patient confidentiality and take no further action","Disclose the information to the sister without patient consent","Wait until the sister independently requests genetic testing","Share the information only with the sister\u0027s General Practitioner"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare providers have an ethical and sometimes legal duty to warn at-risk relatives about genetic conditions when three criteria are met:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe condition is serious\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe risk of development can be quantified\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epreventive measures are available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, \u003Cstrong\u003Edisclosure to the sister without patient consent\u003C/strong\u003E may be justified as BRCA1 variants significantly increase cancer risk and preventive options exist. While patient confidentiality is important, the duty to prevent harm may override this in specific genetic cases such as this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ethical principle of preventing harm (non-maleficence) and promoting benefit (beneficence) to at-risk relatives can outweigh individual patient confidentiality in cases where serious genetic conditions can be prevented or treated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Genetic testing can reveal information about biological relatives, requiring careful consideration of family implications.","Healthcare providers have a duty to warn at-risk relatives about genetic conditions that are serious, preventable, and treatable.","Patient confidentiality must be balanced against the potential benefit to relatives who could take preventive action."],"references":["National Health and Medical Research Council, Ethical Aspects of Human Genetic Testing: An Information Paper, NHMRC. 2003. Available at: www.nhmrc.gov.au/issues/humangenetics.htm"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54148"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16901"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54148"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T10:24:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T10:38:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9591"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68691"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description"